          "body": "From verse 14 onward, the chapter shifts register from narrative to inventory. The narrator lists: 666 talents of gold annually (10:14), 500 golden shields (10:16-17), an ivory-and-gold throne (10:18-20), all-gold drinking vessels (10:21), triennial Tarshish voyages (10:22), and finally 1,400 chariots, 12,000 horsemen, and horses from Egypt (10:26-29). The list is presented without explicit moral commentary — but the reader who carries Deuteronomy 17:14-20 into the text hears the commentary in the silence. Moses had written that the king 'shall not multiply horses for himself, nor shall he cause the people to return to Egypt to multiply horses... he shall not greatly multiply silver and gold for himself' (Deuteronomy 17:16-17). Chapter 10 checks every item on the forbidden list. The narrator's restraint is itself a rhetorical strategy: the indictment is complete, but the reader must supply the verdict. As Howard Hendricks often pressed — the text trusts you to do the work of comparison."
