          "body": "The ivory throne overlaid with refined gold (10:18-20) receives five verses of description — more than any other single object in the chapter. Its architecture is precise: six steps, a rounded top, armrests flanked by lions, and twelve lions standing on the six steps, one on each side of each step. The number six and the imagery of lions recurs in the Davidic royal tradition (cf. Psalm 72:15-17; Ezekiel 19:1-9). But the throne's elaborateness — 'nothing like it was made for any other kingdom' (10:20) — sits in tension with the Mosaic prescription. Deuteronomy 17:18-20 commands that the king keep a copy of the law beside him and read it all his life, 'so that his heart may not be lifted up above his brothers.' The magnificent throne may be precisely the kind of material exaltation the Torah warned against. The physical ascent of six steps to reach the king's seat becomes an emblem of the pride Deuteronomy was designed to prevent."
