          "body": "1 Kings as a whole is a theological history written from the perspective of the Deuteronomic covenant — measuring every king by the standard of fidelity to Yahweh and obedience to Torah. Chapter 10 is the last chapter in which Solomon is presented without explicit condemnation. Chapter 9 had already included God's warning: 'if you or your sons indeed turn away from following Me... then I will cut off Israel from the land' (9:6-7). Chapter 11 will open immediately with Solomon's love for foreign women and the consequent departure of God's approval. Chapter 10 therefore occupies a precise canonical position: it is the fullest possible picture of what Solomon's God-given gifts could produce, immediately before the account of how those gifts were squandered. The chapter is not simply historical reportage; it is the narrator's portrait of what Israel under a fully obedient king might have looked like permanently — and what the nation lost when the king's heart turned. The queen of Sheba left Jerusalem and went home. The wisdom she encountered did not stay with the man who was meant to embody it."
