        "number": 3,
        "title": "666 talents and the arithmetic of excess",
        "range": "10:14-22",
        "excerpt": "Now the weight of gold which came in to Solomon in one year was 666 talents of gold.",
        "body": "The inventory section (10:14-22) functions as a carefully constructed ledger of excess. The opening number — 666 talents of gold annually — has attracted theological attention from early interpreters. Some commentators (cf. John Sailhamer, *The Pentateuch as Narrative*) note the same number in Revelation 13:18, though the contexts are distinct; the connection may be coincidental or may signal that the number carries a connotation of human glory at its maximum, just short of divine perfection (777). More textually grounded is the observation that 666 talents by the ancient Near Eastern standard would be approximately 25 tons of gold per year — a figure that staggers any comparison. For reference, the annual gold revenue of the Persian Empire under Darius I was approximately 360 Euboic talents. Solomon's figure dwarfs it.\n\nThe shields that follow (10:16-17) — 200 large shields at 600 shekels each, 300 smaller shields at 3 minas each — were not functional military equipment but display pieces, stored in the House of the Forest of Lebanon. The narrator does not say 'and Solomon used them in battle.' He says Solomon *made* them and *put* them in the storage building. They are visible wealth masquerading as military readiness. The weight of gold committed to display objects (200 shields × 600 shekels = 120,000 shekels just for the large shields) represents enormous resource devoted to ceremony rather than to the justice and righteousness the queen named in 10:9.\n\nThe ivory throne (10:18-20) receives the section's most detailed architectural description — six steps, lions at each armrest, twelve lions across the steps. The throne's unique status ('nothing like it was made for any other kingdom,' 10:20) is both a historical claim and a narrative warning. The Mosaic law envisioned a king who kept the Torah close at hand and read it daily 'so that his heart may not be lifted up above his brothers' (Deuteronomy 17:20). A throne with no peer in any kingdom, ascending six steps above the court, represents precisely the elevation Deuteronomy feared.\n\nThe section closes with the ultimate statement of abundance: all drinking vessels pure gold, silver not considered valuable in Solomon's day (10:21). This is not economic description alone; it is a portrait of a culture that has reversed the value hierarchy of scarcity — what was precious (silver) has become common. The very success of Solomon's accumulation has destroyed the normal ordering of value. This is the narrator's quiet commentary on excess: when abundance becomes the norm, the categories that orient human life are lost.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Zahav* (gold) appears in its highest density in this section — the word saturates verses 14-22. *Sagar zahav* (pure gold, v.21) — the closing term for refined, shut-in gold, the same term used of the Holy of Holies interior in 1 Kings 6:20. The vocabulary of the Most Holy Place now describes drinking cups. The sacred and commercial have merged."
